div.p:
Hitherto from the beginning of vers. 3. to the end of the 19, the Prophet hath been an humble and affectionate petitioner


for himselfe. Now he becomes an earnest suter vnto the Lord for the Church and common wealth of Israel. The effect of his sute is this: that whereas the heinousnes of his transgressions had iustly occasioned the Lord in iustice to withdraw his fauour from the people vnder Dauids gouernement:


The Lord would be pleased, notwithstanding his sinnes, to aduance the publike good of the Church and common wealth of Israel, vers. 20. in the beginning and end.
